<img class="alignnone wp-image-705244 lazyload" src="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Adegbenga-Kaka-797x598.jpg" alt="" width="960" height="720" srcset="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Adegbenga-Kaka-797x598.jpg 797w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Adegbenga-Kaka-320x240.jpg 320w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Adegbenga-Kaka-640x480.jpg 640w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Adegbenga-Kaka-487x365.jpg 487w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Adegbenga-Kaka-600x450.jpg 600w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Adegbenga-Kaka.jpg 800w" sizes="(max-width: 960px) 100vw, 960px" /> A former deputy governor in Ogun State, Senator Adegbenga Kaka, has declared his intention to join the governorship race in the state. He made the declaration on Monday at the Nigeria Union of Journalists, Ogun State council secretariat at Oke Ilewo, Abeokuta. He said as Ogun State “stands today, there is ample room for improvement in agriculture, education, healthcare, employment and empowerment of our youth and female folks, rural development, sports and tourism. “I am your man, I have the experience, the integrity and commitment.” he added. Kaka was the deputy to the former governor of the state, Chief Olusegun Osoba, and a former Senator who had represented Ogun East in the upper chamber. He said he would be contesting for governorship in 2019 on the platform of the All Progressives Congress.  To enable commenting and other interactive features, please switch to the more advanced .